</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation id="130E2A02FFC7F437F0CB4A77FC84F43C" box="[735,834,1033,1059]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 4" captionStart-1="FIGURE 5" captionStart-2="FIGURE 6" captionStartId-0="5.[151,255,1978,2002]" captionStartId-1="6.[151,255,1977,2001]" captionStartId-2="7.[151,255,1962,1986]" captionTargetBox-0="[200,1402,1260,1949]" captionTargetBox-1="[186,1405,194,1962]" captionTargetBox-2="[176,1415,194,1941]" captionTargetId-0="figure-524@5.[181,1415,1260,1971]" captionTargetId-1="figure-46@6.[186,1405,194,1962]" captionTargetId-2="figure-42@7.[176,1415,194,1941]" captionTargetPageId-0="5" captionTargetPageId-1="6" captionTargetPageId-2="7" captionText-0="FIGURE 4. Drawing of the flower parts of the type specimen of Guzmania inkaterrae A. Floral bract. B. Sepals (abaxial one on the right). C. Petals (the left one separated). D. Stamen E. Pistil." captionText-1="FIGURE 5. Guzmania inkaterrae in habitat A. Epiphytic on small trees in the mountain forest. B. Inflorescence with flowers. C. Plant on a branch, fallen on the forest floor." captionText-2="FIGURE 6. Fertile part of the inflorescence of Guzmania inkaterrae showing some colour variation within the species. More often the inflorescence is more greenish." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5059139" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5059141" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5059143" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5059139/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5059141/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5059143/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="14">Fig. 4–6</figureCitation>
)
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8A3687FFC7F437F2834A33FDDEF4BB" blockId="4.[151,1436,1101,1188]" pageId="4" pageNumber="14">
This new species is characterized by its large size (ca. 
<quantity id="4CCD9B62FFC7F437F1134A33FC9BF47B" box="[775,861,1101,1124]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="4" pageNumber="14" unit="cm" value="130.0">130 cm</quantity>
), its elongate peduncle and dense globose to ovoid inflorescence, that is in general not very colourful, with relatively large floral bracts (3.5 × 2.0 cm), flowers (
<quantity id="4CCD9B62FFC7F437F75E4A13FA53F49B" box="[1354,1429,1133,1156]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="4" pageNumber="14" unit="cm" value="4.5">4.5 cm</quantity>
) and sepals (27 × 9.5–11.0 mm).
</paragraph>
